Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

Shared Pool Advisory

  • SP: Shared Pool Est LC: Estimated Library Cache Factr: Factor
  • Note there is often a 1:Many correlation between a single logical object in the Library Cache, and the physical number of memory objects associated with it. Therefore comparing the number of Lib Cache objects (e.g. in v$librarycache), with the number of Lib Cache Memory Objects is invalid.

Undo Segment Summary

  • Min/Max TR (mins) - Min and Max Tuned Retention (minutes)

  • Undo segment block stats:
  • uS - unexpired Stolen, uR - unexpired Released, uU - unexpired reUsed
  • eS - expired Stolen, eR - expired Released, eU - expired reUsed

Finding 7: Undersized SGA
Impact is .09 active sessions, 5.84% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "20032 M" during the analysis period.

Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
Estimated benefit is .04 active sessions, 2.96% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------------------
Action
Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to
27544 M.

Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
---------------------------------
Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
Impact is .42 active sessions, 28.32% of total activity.
Hard parsing of SQL statements was consuming significant database time.
Impact is .35 active sessions, 24.16% of total activity.


Finding 8: Hard Parse Due to Sharing Criteria
Impact is .07 active sessions, 4.68% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
SQL statements with the same text were not shared because of cursor
environment mismatch. This resulted in additional hard parses which were
consuming significant database time.
Common causes of environment mismatch are session NLS settings, SQL trace
settings and optimizer parameters.

Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
Estimated benefit is .07 active sessions, 4.68% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------------------
Action
Look for top reason for cursor environment mismatch in
V$SQL_SHARED_CURSOR.

Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
---------------------------------
Hard parsing of SQL statements was consuming significant database time.
Impact is .35 active sessions, 24.16% of total activity.


Finding 9: Global Cache Messaging
Impact is .07 active sessions, 4.64% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Inter-instance messaging was consuming significant database time on this
instance.

Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
Estimated benefit is .07 active sessions, 4.64% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------------------
Action
Look at the "Top SQL Statements" finding for SQL statements consuming
significant time on Cluster waits. For example, the SELECT statement
with SQL_ID "5unf2z5p1b59k" is responsible for 33% of Cluster wait
during the analysis period.

Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
---------------------------------
Wait class "Cluster" was consuming significant database time.
Impact is .07 active sessions, 4.64% of total activity.


Finding 10: Hard Parse Due to Invalidations
Impact is .06 active sessions, 4.11% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Cursors were getting invalidated due to DDL operations. This resulted in
additional hard parses which were consuming significant database time.

Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
Estimated benefit is .06 active sessions, 4.11% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------------------
Action
Investigate appropriateness of DDL operations.

Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
---------------------------------
Hard parsing of SQL statements was consuming significant database time.
Impact is .35 active sessions, 24.16% of total activity.
